-- Asur, Eletrobras, Eletropaulo, OSX Brasil: Latin American Equity Preview
-- Nathan Gill
-- 2010-06-30T04:17:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-30/asur-eletrobras-eletropaulo-osx-brasil-latin-american-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Latin American trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous
close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  fell 4.4 percent to 3,694.19.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  
 Brazil  
 Centrais Eletricas Brasileiras SA  (ELET6 BS): The outlook
for Latin America’s biggest utility was raised to positive from
stable by Fitch Ratings, citing the country’s “better-than-
expected resilience and economic performance in the face of the
global recession.” Eletrobras, as the state-controlled company
is known, fell 0.9 percent to 28.85 reais.  
 Eletropaulo Metropolitana SA  (ELPL6 BS): Brazil’s
electricity regulator, known as Aneel, said the Brazilian unit
of AES Corp. could increase rates by an average 0.9 percent
starting July 4. Eletropaulo slid 0.6 percent to 36.79 reais.  
 OSX Brasil SA  (OSXB3 BZ): The shipbuilder controlled by
Brazilian billionaire  Eike Batista  submitted bids to help build
two drilling rigs for Petroleo Brasileiro SA, OSX Chief
Financial Officer  Roberto Monteiro  said yesterday in Rio de
Janeiro. OSX lost 3.8 percent to 485 reais.  
 Chile  
 Parque Arauco SA  (PARAUCO CC): A unit of the Chilean
shopping mall operator, Inmuebles Comerciales del Peru SAC, may
auction $30 million in bonds in Lima in the coming days, Peru’s
securities regulator said yesterday. Parque Arauco fell 0.3
percent to 747.83 pesos.  
 Mexico  
 BBVA Bancomer SA  (BBVA* MM): The Mexican unit  of Banco
Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria SA  will invest $2 billion in Mexico
during the next three years, BBVA Bancomer President  Ignacio Deschamps  said. BBVA shares fell 6 percent to 130.6 reais.  
 Grupo Aeroportuario del Sureste SAB  (ASURB MM): U.S.
airline Virgin America Inc. said it plans to begin service to
Mexican cities, including Cancun, before year’s end, pending
regulatory approval, according to a company statement yesterday.
Asur, as the operator of Cancun’s airport is known, is known,
fell 5.5 percent to 58.84 pesos.  
 Kimberly-Clark de Mexico SAB  (KIMBERA MM): Economy Minister
 Gerardo Ruiz Mateos  said the country will create about 750,000
jobs this year as the economy rebounds from a recession and
foreign direct investment increases, more than the central
bank’s forecast of between 500,000 and 600,000. The biggest
consumer products company fell 2.8 percent to 74.26 pesos.  
